     <p><strong><p><strong>Elizabeth Barnes, <em>Health Problems: Philosophical Puzzles about the Nature of Health</em>, Oxford University Press, 2023, 302pp., $30.00 (hbk), ISBN 9780192883476. </strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Alison Reiheld, Southern Illinois University, Edwardsville</strong></p>
     <p>Think of how it feels to be sick, or to care for someone else who is sick. What has gone missing? Or what is this new thing that is present? What is it we are doing when we try to “eat healthy” or “be healthy” or “avoid unhealthy lifestyle choices”? And why does it matter so much? Why is it so powerful to say “I just want you to be healthy”? Why are health-behavior-related comments, including whether a person is “health-conscious”, showing up in dating apps? When is a change in our condition a loss of health, or “normal aging”, or just our mortal frames doing the things that mortal frames do, which is to say, beginning to fall apart just about as soon as...
